Methods

Microbial abundance was analyzed using proportional odds logistic regression (POLR) [1], which we use here as a semi-parametric regression method for continuous data as described in [2]. P-values were adjusted for multiple testing across ARGs using the Benjamini-Hochberg false discovery rate (FDR) controlling method [3].

Analyses were conducted using R version 4.0.1 (2020-06-06) [4]. POLR models were fitted using the function polr in the R package MASS, version 7.3-53.

  1. McCullagh, P. (1980). Regression Models for Ordinal Data. Journal of the Royal Statistical Society. Series B (Methodological), 42(2), 109-142.

  2. Liu Q, Shepherd BE, Li C, Harrell FE Jr. Modeling continuous response variables using ordinal regression. Stat Med. 2017;36(27):4316-4335. doi:10.1002/sim.7433

  3. Benjamini, Y., & Hochberg, Y. (1995). Controlling the False Discovery Rate: A Practical and Powerful Approach to Multiple Testing. Journal of the Royal Statistical Society. Series B (Methodological), 57(1), 289-300.

  4. R Core Team (2020). R: A language and environment for statistical computing. R Foundation for Statistical Computing, Vienna, Austria. URL https://www.R-project.org/.

Derive low and high fiber groups based on average fiber

tmp <- ifelse(sample_data(ps)$avg_fibe_tnfs <= avg_fibe_tnfs.quartiles["25%"] &
        sample_data(ps)$dt_fibe <= dt_fibe.quartiles["25%"], "Low", NA)
tmp <- ifelse(sample_data(ps)$avg_fibe_tnfs >= avg_fibe_tnfs.quartiles["75%"] &
        sample_data(ps)$dt_fibe >= dt_fibe.quartiles["75%"], "High", tmp)
tmp <- factor(tmp, levels = c("Low", "High"))
sample_data(ps)$avg_fiber_cat <- tmp

Derive low and high fiber groups based on fiber per kCal

tmp <- ifelse(sample_data(ps)$perKcal_fiber_tnfs <= perKcal_fiber_tnfs.quartiles["25%"] &
        sample_data(ps)$FFQ_fiber_per_kCal <= FFQ_fiber_per_kCal.quartiles["25%"], "Low", NA)
tmp <- ifelse(sample_data(ps)$perKcal_fiber_tnfs >= 14 &
        sample_data(ps)$FFQ_fiber_per_kCal >= 14, "Adequate", tmp)

sample_data(ps)$per_kCal_fiber_cat <- tmp

In addition to the above filtering, results are not reported for ARGs for which the POLR fitter generated a warning that fitted values of 0 or 1 had been generated, indicating quasi-complete separation, likely due to too few non-zero observations.

Function to fit POLR model given OTU table, data frame with metadata, and formula

fit.polr <- function(formula, ps, caption, outfile){
    y <- otu_table(ps)
    pdata <- as.data.frame(unclass(sample_data(ps)))
    tax <- as.data.frame(unclass(tax_table(ps)))
    tax$ID <- rownames(tax)
    tmp <- lapply(rownames(y), function(x){
            df <- pdata
            df$y <- as.numeric(y[x,])
            f <- formula(paste(paste("factor(y)", deparse(formula)), collapse = " "))
            mod <- tryCatch(polr(f, df), error = function(e)e, warning = function(e)e)
            if (inherits(mod, "polr")){
                p <- Anova(mod)$`Pr(>Chisq)`[1]
                coef <- as.numeric(coef(mod)[1])
                return(c(Coefficient = coef, P.Value = p))
            } else{
                return(NULL)    
            }
    })
    names(tmp) <- rownames(y)
    tmp <- do.call(rbind, tmp) 
    tmp <- as.data.frame(tmp)
    tmp <- arrange(tmp, P.Value)
    tmp$adj.P.Val <- p.adjust(tmp$P.Value, "BH")
    tmp$ID <- rownames(tmp)
    tmp <- left_join(tmp, tax, by = "ID")
    tmp <- select(tmp, ID, everything())
    write.table(tmp, outfile, quote = F, sep = "\t", row.names = F)
    header <- ncol(tmp)
    names(header) <- paste("Output is in the file", outfile)
    tab <- kable(tmp, caption = caption, row.names = F) %>% kable_styling() %>% 
        add_header_above(c(header)) %>%
        scroll_box(height = "500px") 
    return(tab)
}

Results

Output includes the following columns:

  • Coefficient: Model coefficient. A positive value indicates higher abundance in the group listed first or an increase in abundance with an increase in a continuous covariate. The coefficient is the log odds ratio for the odds of a higher versus lower abundance, regardless of what cutoff is used to define "higher" and "lower".

  • P.Value: Raw p-value for the test that the coefficient differs from 0

  • adj.P.Val: Benjamini-Hochberg false discovery rate (FDR) adjusted p-value

Average fiber category

No covariates
